Statius alludes to the legendary origin of Corinthian bronze from the mixing of metals when the city was destroyed by Mummius3 a burlesque version of this legend is put into the mouth of Trimalchio (Petron. e. 50), who tells his guests that Hannibal, when he took Troy, melted in one pile all the statues of gold, silver, and bronze, and that Corinthia were made from the fragments of this mass. Inscriptions show that collectors had slaves (a Corinthiis) whose sole duty was to take charge of these bronzes. Verres was proscribed (43 A-D.), and so lost his life at the same time as his prosecutor Cicero, because os his Corinthia which Antony coveted (Pliny Mzt. Hist. xxxiv 6).
